commentBody:
@B 

Thanks for writing what I was thinking!

I turned off the overlays almost immediately, and found the gray squares easier on my eyes. Unfortunately, I hadn’t yet grasped the significance of the colors. For all I knew, (GREEN) GIANT is now just GIANT, but then I buy the store-brand frozen spinach and broccoli. But as you said, the answers were simple enough to grasp the color component easily.

@sotto voce

Wait, what, “zooming”?

I don’t know if I never tried before or if it’s only recently been possible, but thanks to your comment, I will never need to squint again to see those oh-so-tiny Sunday numbers. Just pinch-zoom (or unpinch-zoom?) works, at least on the iOS app. 👏

@Mike 

Now you've shown your true colors.

/Emus in the shade, not ex-tint

@HeathieJ 

Thanks for that.  Wow that looks dumb.  I had naively assumed it meant a physical support stand for the keg.

Now I like that puzzle even less.

@RI guy 

I second your recommendation about supporting xwordinfo.com. I had never heard of it until I started reading these comments a few years ago. It’s a fantastic trove of information about the NYT puzzles. 

And Jim Horne and Jeff Chen seem like nice guys. I’ve emailed them many times about things like old puzzles with opaque themes, and Jim has always replied promptly.

@Steve L 

So you’re telling me I filled in a Spice Girls answer and didn’t even notice it?

Then what was the point of the hours I devoted to learning their names?

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight 

How would we have been able to distinguish black squares that needed filling from the other black squares in the grid?

Maybe the gray just needed to be darker, with white letters.

@Jerome 
I can't imagine trying to solve this on a phone.  Even on a computer with a 27 inch monitor, I had to up the magnification from 150% to 175%.

I hope all the effort was worth it!

@CCNY 
I figured there were eight "otto"mans in set.

How many emus are there in a set??????

@Mean Old Lady 
Never mind....I forgot that was part of a RING, so I needed to add the color.

The grid (in progress) looked like a lawn after the armadillos dropped in overnight.

@Mean Old Lady 

100A is part of the green Olympic ring, so a green HOUSE has a lot of room to grow (plants).



Emus can run rings around us mere solvers.

@Barry Ancona 

I just go to the crossword page, then hit Print for the pdf. I don't see the full grid until the pdf pops up, and there was nothing in the pdf that indicated I needed to look at the "newspaper version".  Therefore, no colors. 
Usually, you can tell if there's something tricky going on in the grid that requires the newspaper version, but that was not obvious to me with this grid.

@SuzyQ Very similar experience! Got a happy glow just seeing the grid. Figured out the rings immediately, but didn't pick up on the added color meaning until STONE.
Then got tripped up trying to make the middle ring gray. I know, I know, but I haven't been watching the Olympics this time and the rings had obviously paled a wee bit in memory.

Only once did I have trouble seeing which square was being highlighted, but then reading the clue solved that. Wondered how it was for those on other platforms, though, so not surprised to see the comments.

@Barry, you beat me to it. 

Sam in Sammamish (Hanadahguyus state), formerly of Nuevo México, or Yootó Hahoodzo. 

Shalom.

@JD 

Or, just maybe, it's a real issue that has affected many people in different ways, and the NYT Games "teams" should take note of what a user interface disaster this was, and try to do better next time?

So sorry the individuals reporting their issues have affected your sensibilities.

@Becca 
"Yes someone above suggested maybe NYT coulda used black squares w/white font— which sounds kinda cool"
If you do the puzzle on-line, yes it would be very cool, but if you do it with pencil and paper.....

@Kathy Carter

Und is German for "and", so a connecting word at an airport in Germany would be UND.

Auf Wiedersehen!

@Michael 

It's old timey slang for a body of water, especially the ocean.  

!

@Zack 

An accessibility accommodation is very important and needs to be heard by the Games team directly. 

And your comment is very well put. I highly recommend copy/pasting it into an email to customer support! (The address is provided at the top of the comments page under the text box where you entered your comment.)

@RozzieGrandma
You're right.  I thought that was a fairly poor clue / answer. 

/Emus think ottomans are their friends

@William 

Exactly - all they needed to do was a better job of reverse highlighting the selected word, perhaps turning entry text white.

It's called user acceptance testing.  They didn't do any.
